WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.760
 So now we're going to bring all this together

00:00:01.760 --> 00:00:05.840
 and we're going to build a simple multi-user chat application

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:10.160
 that moves data through the server using Ajax and JSON.

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:12.320
 So the idea here is we've got a simple chat

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:15.040
 and things are going to happen.

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:18.640
 And we're going to use two tabs to simulate two users.

00:00:18.640 --> 00:00:21.680
 And the idea is whatever you enter in the first tab,

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:24.880
 it's going to asynchronously merely appear in the second tab.

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:26.960
 And we're going to use polling to do this.

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:28.800
 And we're going to use polling every four seconds,

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:31.040
 which is a very inefficient way to do this.

00:00:31.040 --> 00:00:33.040
 But for now, it's the simplest way

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:35.920
 I can show you in a hurry what's going on.

00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:40.320
 Every four seconds, both windows are making a request

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:44.720
 to this URL called messages that is a JSON endpoint.

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:49.280
 And they get back an array of the recent messages,

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:53.040
 both the message text and a little nice time indicator,

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:56.560
 like a minute ago or two minutes ago or something like that.

00:00:56.560 --> 00:00:58.720
 And so this happens every four seconds.

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:00.880
 And that's why this is not at all best practice.

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:03.200
 Not only is it not best practice for that,

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:05.120
 but I'm returning an array in JSON.

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:06.800
 And you're really not supposed to do that.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:08.080
 You're supposed to return an object.

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:10.160
 Even if the main data is an array,

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:11.920
 you want an outer encapsulating object.

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:15.040
 But again, I'm trying to keep this as simple and short

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:16.320
 as I possibly can.

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:18.560
 So if we take a look at the urls.py,

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:19.920
 and again, I got a nice walkthrough

00:01:19.920 --> 00:01:22.080
 if you want to see this version in walkthrough.

00:01:22.080 --> 00:01:24.960
 I have the main view that's talk.

00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:28.720
 And then messages is that JSON view.

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:33.600
 And I have a little spinner that you can see

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:34.640
 when it first starts up.

00:01:34.640 --> 00:01:37.280
 And then there's a simple model where we've got some text

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:39.920
 and who typed it in and what time it was created

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:40.960
 and if there's any updating.

00:01:40.960 --> 00:01:42.320
 In this case, there's no updating.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:44.240
 But we need the date of the thing

00:01:44.240 --> 00:01:45.840
 so we can say it's two minutes ago.

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:50.800
 And so if you take a look at the views.py,

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:56.240
 the talk main simply shows the main page and then is done.

00:01:56.240 --> 00:01:58.640
 And when we hit the chat button or post button,

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:01.440
 it comes back to the post and we save the message.

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:04.480
 And then we redirect back to ourselves, back to the talk.

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:09.600
 So if you look at the template, talk.htm,

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:11.360
 you see we have a simple form.

00:02:11.360 --> 00:02:14.560
 That's got a text field and a submit button named post.

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:18.160
 And importantly, this div id chat content

00:02:18.160 --> 00:02:22.560
 that has a spinning GIF as its content.

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:24.560
 And you're gonna see that we're gonna delete this.

00:02:24.560 --> 00:02:28.080
 And so one of the reasons I make it wait two seconds

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:30.000
 is that you can see this when it comes up

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.160
 and you can see the spinner happening.

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:33.920
 But then once the JavaScript takes over,

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:37.600
 it actually deletes the spinner and replaces it with the messages.

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:41.280
 So this div is a placeholder for us to put the chat content,

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:44.960
 which we're going to put in using JavaScript.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:46.400
 And here's the main JavaScript.

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:50.480
 We have a function called updateMessage and it does a fetch.

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:54.560
 And it does a fetch to the URL messages.

00:02:54.560 --> 00:02:58.480
 The cache node storage just says every time I ask to fetch it,

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:00.320
 give me a new copy of it.

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:01.840
 And then I have a couple of promises.

00:03:01.840 --> 00:03:05.120
 The first promise says the response has been started

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:07.680
 and I'd like to retrieve the response and convert it

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:09.760
 as if it were JSON data.

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:12.320
 And then the second promise takes as its parameters

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:18.800
 the converted JSON data, meaning the rows with a Z is an object,

00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:20.400
 which in this case is an array.

00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:25.840
 And so we basically log that so we can see it.

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:29.680
 Then we go and say document get all my ID chat content.

00:03:29.680 --> 00:03:30.480
 That's that div.

00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:31.680
 InnerHTML is nothing.

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:35.760
 That is deleting either the previous list of messages

00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:36.720
 or the spinner.

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:39.680
 So we're gonna empty it out and then we're gonna fill it back up.

00:03:40.560 --> 00:03:43.440
 So we're gonna loop through this set of rows that we got back.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:49.120
 And for each row, we're going to append a paragraph tag.

00:03:49.120 --> 00:03:52.640
 So plus equals there is appending to the current innerHTML.

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:55.680
 We can just treat this innerHTML as a variable, right?

00:03:55.680 --> 00:03:57.200
 We can read it and we can write it.

00:03:57.200 --> 00:03:59.520
 And plus equals means we're appending to it.

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:00.720
 We append a p tag.

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:03.040
 We append the first part of the row, which is the message.

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:06.160
 Then a br tag and two non-breaking spaces.

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:08.800
 And then the second part, which is how long ago it was,

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:10.720
 which we generated in the server.

00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:12.240
 And then an end of a p tag.

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:16.000
 And then we set a timeout so that we do this again in four seconds,

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.160
 4,000 milliseconds actually.

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:20.560
 And then there's a catch that just alerts.

00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:23.440
 Now, the way this stuff usually works is that

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:28.080
 it usually works or it blows up badly.

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:31.040
 And so I just have a catch that says here's the error.

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:33.280
 And hopefully it doesn't happen very often,

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:37.360
 but maybe the error could either be I made a mistake in the server.

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:38.800
 And if you're doing software development,

00:04:38.800 --> 00:04:41.040
 chances are good that you're going to make a mistake in the server.

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:43.200
 And that's a reason to put this alert there.

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:45.520
 In the real world, once your server code is nice and clean

00:04:45.520 --> 00:04:46.960
 and doesn't have errors in it,

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:49.760
 then they probably lost their network connection

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:52.000
 or your server went down or something like that

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
 in the middle of every four seconds getting this new data.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.480
 And then at the end, we have an event listener, DOMContentLoaded,

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:01.920
 which we've talked about before.

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:07.200
 And we simply run a function to do a set timeout of update message

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:10.000
 two seconds after the DOMContent is loaded.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.320
 And that's what these lines tell us to do.

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:15.440
 And remember that update message doesn't actually call it right there.

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:16.560
 It's in a string.

00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:19.120
 And it says after two seconds,

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:23.920
 parse this JavaScript string and run it.

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:25.200
 And that's what's happening here.

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:28.080
 So we take a look at views.py.

00:05:28.080 --> 00:05:30.480
 We're doing a GET request.

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:33.040
 And this is the one where we're sending a JSON response.

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:35.600
 We're going to retrieve the messages,

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:40.480
 the most recent 10 messages ordered into sending order by created at.

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:42.320
 And then we're going to process it.

00:05:42.320 --> 00:05:47.120
 Now, it's pretty common not to just send the objects back.

00:05:47.120 --> 00:05:49.120
 We want to do a little processing.

00:05:49.120 --> 00:05:52.000
 And so we're sending back the message text.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.400
 And then this natural time, which is a Django library

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:57.360
 that makes up this 13 minutes ago, 14 minutes ago.

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:01.200
 We go through the array that is the list of objects

00:06:01.200 --> 00:06:03.280
 that we got from Django's model.

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:06.560
 And then we're going to make another one,

00:06:06.560 --> 00:06:10.000
 which is the only the pieces we want to give to our front end code.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.800
 And then we return a JSON response with results,

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:15.760
 which is an array, which then is serialized into an array.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:18.160
 And it's actually an array of arrays.

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:22.480
 And that is serialized then into an array of an arrays and sent back to it.

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:25.280
 And then we go back to the code here.

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:30.560
 If you look there, that is looping through the data

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:34.880
 that came back from the messages view in JSON.

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:37.200
 And so, you know, again, that's what happens.

00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:41.360
 It's just every four seconds, it runs through and retrieves the JSON,

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:45.120
 clears out that div, then fills it back up with whatever they are.

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:48.160
 And if nothing changed, you don't even see a blanket.

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:53.840
 It all happens so rapidly, partly because it's all done asynchronously.

00:06:53.840 --> 00:06:57.440
 And that is that we are not actually touching the DOM

00:06:57.440 --> 00:07:00.160
 until we've got the data to replace it.

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:03.120
 And then we do it so fast and we're done.

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:06.640
 And then we give the browser back the thread and then it redisplays,

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:09.360
 which means it's not kind of displaying one piece at a time.

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:14.240
 You are modifying the DOM and it doesn't update the window

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:17.600
 until you return from the function.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:21.600
 So in summary, JSON is very powerful.

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:24.640
 These are pretty short lectures, actually.

00:07:24.640 --> 00:07:30.000
 It is very well supported and performs extremely well in many languages.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.400
 I mean, it's over 20 years old now.

00:07:32.400 --> 00:07:38.160
 And every language has to be really good at JSON.

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:41.360
 Back in the early days, you'd have to go find a JSON library.

00:07:41.360 --> 00:07:42.880
 Now it's just built in.

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:46.560
 It's built into the browsers, it's built into Python, it's built into PHP.

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:47.920
 It's built into everything.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:52.560
 And so Python and Django and JavaScript have excellent support.

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:55.200
 So it's a great way to build applications.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:05.200
 [MUSIC]

